{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491663"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1015"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1015"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.16,0.62,0.02,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1015"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53644"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1015"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1015"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39105"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"333"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5772"},{"type":"tags","id":"9076"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53644"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of generalised colicky abdominal pain. She has not opened her bowels for the last two days. She has no significant medical history and no previous abdominal surgery. She does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended and soft. There are no abdominal wall hernias. Bowel sounds are increased and tinkling. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely way that the gallstone got from point A to point B?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholecystogastric fistula","Through the cystic and common bile ducts","Cholecystoduodenal fistula","Aberrant cystic duct","Cholecystocolonic fistula"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows dilated loops of small bowel, suggesting obstruction. This is an example of gallstone ileus, a rare form of mechanical small bowel obstruction caused by impaction of a large gallstone in the intestine - the term \u0022ileus\u0022 is a misnomer in this instance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echolecystoduodenal fistula\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common and likely route for a large gallstone to enter the intestinal tract. This fistula typically forms as a result of chronic inflammation from cholecystitis. The inflamed gallbladder becomes adherent to the adjacent duodenum, and over time, a fistula develops. A large stone can then pass through this fistula and become impacted in the small intestine, most commonly in the ileum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Echolecystogastric fistulas\u003C/strong\u003E can occur, they are less common than cholecystoduodenal fistulas. Even if a stone passed through such a fistula, it would still need to traverse the pylorus and duodenum before causing obstruction in the small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPassage \u003Cstrong\u003Ethrough the cystic and common bile ducts\u003C/strong\u003E is the usual route for smaller gallstones to enter the duodenum. However, stones large enough to cause obstruction are unlikely to pass through this pathway due to the narrow diameter of these ducts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eaberrant cystic duct\u003C/strong\u003E is an anatomical variation in the biliary system. While it might affect gallbladder drainage, it would not provide a direct route for a large gallstone to enter the intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echolecystocolonic fistula\u003C/strong\u003E is another possible, but less common, route for gallstones to enter the intestinal tract. However, stones passing through this type of fistula would enter the colon rather than the small intestine, making it an unlikely explanation for small bowel obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of gallstone ileus is often based on Rigler\u0027s triad: pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone. Treatment typically involves surgical removal of the obstructing stone, with debate ongoing about whether to address the biliary-enteric fistula in the same operation or as a staged procedure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gallstone ileus is an uncommon cause of small bowel obstruction, typically occurring through a cholecystoduodenal fistula.","Radiological findings of pneumobilia, small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone (Rigler\u0027s triad) are characteristic of gallstone ileus."],"references":["Inukai K. Gallstone ileus: a review. BMJ Open Gastro 2019;6:1-4. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31875141/","Jacobucci J, Lee E, Price D, et al. Gallstone ileus. American College of Surgeons Case Reviews. 2023. Available at: https://www.facs.org/for-medical-professionals/news-publications/journals/case-reviews/issues/v3n8/jacobucci-gallstone-ileus/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39105"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1015"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15878"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15878"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4ae4119d-ddbf-46a3-baa1-cfbacee84bc1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4ae4119d-ddbf-46a3-baa1-cfbacee84bc1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":401,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39105"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T16:28:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T16:29:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1015"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53644"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{